They're really rare in the wild.

00:00:42.959 --> 00:00:45.759
I do have like two more.

00:00:45.759 --> 00:00:48.240
So come find me.

00:00:48.240 --> 00:00:51.320
In any case, whatever brings you here, welcome.

00:00:51.320 --> 00:00:54.000
RStudio Conf is one of my favorite things in the world.

00:00:54.000 --> 00:00:56.360
I have to say that very carefully.

00:00:56.360 --> 00:01:02.320
It's one of my favorites because I think my wife and kids are watching.

00:01:02.320 --> 00:01:05.800
Just to be clear, they are my favorite.

00:01:05.800 --> 00:01:09.080
RStudio is close, though.

00:01:09.080 --> 00:01:10.320
Okay.

00:01:10.320 --> 00:01:17.639
So if this is you, where you look at the tidyverse code and you're like, wow, that is beautiful.

00:01:17.639 --> 00:01:22.040
But then you also feel this when you look at data table code.

00:01:22.040 --> 00:01:24.160
I understand nothing.

00:01:24.160 --> 00:01:27.199
That is okay.

00:01:27.199 --> 00:01:30.160
That is expected for this audience for the most part.

00:01:30.160 --> 00:01:32.800
I know a lot of people have used data table.

00:01:32.800 --> 00:01:39.879
However, my goal today is to show how the tidyverse and data table are complementary.

00:01:39.879 --> 00:01:44.519
And to show that, I'm going to show it using list columns and how they're beneficial and

00:01:44.519 --> 00:01:47.720
how you can use them in data table.

00:01:47.720 --> 00:01:51.279
So to start, what even is a list column?

00:01:51.400 --> 00:01:57.320
I'm curious, how many have purposefully used a list column in their work?

00:01:57.320 --> 00:01:58.559
You guys are awesome.

00:01:58.559 --> 00:01:59.559
It's about half.

00:01:59.559 --> 00:02:00.559
That's awesome.

00:02:00.559 --> 00:02:06.400
So for those that haven't, a list column is basically where you take some subset of the

00:02:06.400 --> 00:02:12.160
data, either a vector or a data table, or there's a bunch of other things you can put

00:02:12.160 --> 00:02:17.160
in there, and you group them into a single column.

00:02:17.160 --> 00:02:23.800
So this example shows we have this data, and then we nest it.

00:02:23.800 --> 00:02:28.839
There's a group nest function in dplyr.

00:02:28.839 --> 00:02:33.039
And essentially what it does is it grabs all the data that's associated with group one

00:02:33.039 --> 00:02:37.199
and shoves it right here into a single cell.

00:02:37.199 --> 00:02:39.399
What's cool about this is you can put all sorts of stuff in here.

00:02:39.399 --> 00:02:40.440
You can put expressions.

00:02:40.440 --> 00:02:44.759
You can put visualizations like ggplot code.

00:02:44.759 --> 00:02:47.119
All of that stuff can go into a list column.

00:02:47.119 --> 00:02:52.039
But you may be wondering, like, why would you want to do that?

00:02:52.039 --> 00:02:54.520
That is weird.

00:02:54.520 --> 00:02:57.160
That's at least my first impression when I saw a list column.

00:02:57.160 --> 00:03:00.279
I was like, you just can't stop, can you?

00:03:00.279 --> 00:03:03.839
You just always want to add something new.

00:03:03.839 --> 00:03:05.720
But really, it is a great question.

00:03:05.720 --> 00:03:08.199
Why would we want to use this?

00:03:08.199 --> 00:03:11.880
I've compiled a short list of some of the reasons.

00:03:11.880 --> 00:03:16.419
The first is that there's several functions in the tidyverse, which means it must be cool.

00:03:16.419 --> 00:03:18.839
So that's one reason to learn it.

00:03:18.839 --> 00:03:24.759
I'm going to show today that it can make some data manipulations actually safer.

00:03:24.759 --> 00:03:29.199
You can avoid some common problems by using a list column.

00:03:29.199 --> 00:03:30.399
It's also memory efficient.

00:03:30.399 --> 00:03:34.520
So if you're working with really big data, a list column can reduce redundancies in your

00:03:34.520 --> 00:03:36.199
data.

00:03:36.240 --> 00:03:42.839
And in some cases, it can even make understanding what you're looking at, your data, much simpler

00:03:42.839 --> 00:03:46.080
when your data is really complex.

00:03:46.080 --> 00:03:49.520
And the last reason I had was it just is going to show up.

00:03:49.520 --> 00:03:54.039
If you've ever used something like Benchmark, it's there.

00:03:54.039 --> 00:03:55.039
And you can't avoid them.

00:03:55.039 --> 00:03:56.479
They're just going to show up in your life.

00:03:56.479 --> 00:04:01.240
So it's good to get to know list columns a little bit.

00:04:01.240 --> 00:04:05.259
On the other hand, why data table?

00:04:05.320 --> 00:04:12.860
We have tons of amazing tools, especially stuff that we've learned here at RStudioConf.

00:04:12.860 --> 00:04:19.899
According to the readme, they give these six reasons why a data table is important.

00:04:19.899 --> 00:04:23.299
I'm going to focus on these first three.

00:04:23.299 --> 00:04:25.380
The first one, a concise syntax.

00:04:25.380 --> 00:04:30.619
So data table, it's built up with these parts right here.

00:04:30.619 --> 00:04:33.339
You start with your data table.

00:04:33.420 --> 00:04:36.299
We'll call it DT for short.

00:04:36.299 --> 00:04:40.179
In the square brackets, you have three main parts.

00:04:40.179 --> 00:04:42.660
There's other parts that you can use, but there's three main ones.

00:04:42.660 --> 00:04:45.700
There's I, J, and by.

00:04:45.700 --> 00:04:54.380
So to translate that, after talking about translating, into dplyr verbs, I, you can

00:04:54.380 --> 00:04:58.700
think of that as either a filter or a range.

00:04:58.700 --> 00:05:04.339
So the things that you would normally put in those two, you would put in I.

00:05:04.339 --> 00:05:07.019
In J, you can think mutate.

00:05:07.019 --> 00:05:11.660
So when you see code in that place, think mutate.

00:05:11.660 --> 00:05:13.500
What would I put in mutate?

00:05:13.500 --> 00:05:15.579
Then by is like group by.

00:05:15.579 --> 00:05:19.079
So I'm going to show some examples that highlight exactly what those look like, but whenever

00:05:19.079 --> 00:05:26.260
you're seeing the I, J, by, I often translate that in my head to filter or range, mutate

00:05:26.260 --> 00:05:29.980
and group by.

00:05:29.980 --> 00:05:32.459
Next thing is that it's really fast.

00:05:32.459 --> 00:05:38.380
That may be the only reason why you're here is you heard that it's really fast.

00:05:38.380 --> 00:05:42.820
Responding to why data table is so fast, this is what Hadley, I don't know if you've heard

00:05:42.820 --> 00:05:45.260
of him, this is what he said.

00:05:45.260 --> 00:05:49.940
I think it's a relentless focus on performance across the entire package.

00:05:49.940 --> 00:05:50.940
And I think this is true.

00:05:50.940 --> 00:05:59.019
I've contributed a little bit to the data table package, and every time they pause and

00:05:59.019 --> 00:06:05.739
look at anything that could be slowing down your code or using up extra memory.

00:06:05.739 --> 00:06:08.839
And they do it to a crazy degree.

00:06:08.839 --> 00:06:09.980
And it's really paid off.

00:06:09.980 --> 00:06:14.059
The package is incredibly fast.

00:06:14.059 --> 00:06:18.299
Which also goes along with it being very memory efficient.

00:06:18.299 --> 00:06:25.619
This was an analysis done by Matt Dow, the creator of data table.

00:06:25.619 --> 00:06:28.820
This was with a huge data set.

00:06:28.820 --> 00:06:35.359
Might not be huge to some of you if you're working with a lot of flowing data.

00:06:35.359 --> 00:06:39.380
This one has a billion rows and nine columns.

00:06:39.380 --> 00:06:43.260
It's about 50 gigabytes of memory.

00:06:43.260 --> 00:06:47.700
He compared all these different frameworks, and for the most part, they either just ran

00:06:47.700 --> 00:06:53.899
out of time or couldn't even start.

00:06:53.899 --> 00:07:02.220
With data table, it was able to accomplish a fairly complex summing by group request

00:07:02.220 --> 00:07:08.100
in a reasonable amount of time, too.

00:07:08.100 --> 00:07:13.500
So because you have such a great framework in the Tidyverse and you have such great performance

00:07:13.500 --> 00:07:18.940
in the data table package, I say let's team up.

00:07:18.940 --> 00:07:19.940
Let's make them work together.

00:07:19.940 --> 00:07:26.220
And so for today's example, we're going to work with some grammar that's provided with

00:07:26.220 --> 00:07:27.220
the Tidyverse.

00:07:27.220 --> 00:07:28.859
It's nest and unnest.

00:07:28.859 --> 00:07:33.140
So nesting, when you think of that, it's making a list column of data tables or vectors or

00:07:33.140 --> 00:07:36.179
visualizations.

00:07:36.179 --> 00:07:40.940
Unnest is unnesting those list columns back into what we normally think of in data frames

00:07:40.940 --> 00:07:45.100
or data tables.

00:07:45.100 --> 00:07:48.760
So in order to highlight this, I'm going to go through a brief example.

00:07:48.760 --> 00:07:54.779
We're going to use data from Statistica and data from the dplyr package of the Star Wars

00:07:54.779 --> 00:07:56.700
data.

00:07:56.700 --> 00:07:59.820
So this has actually become really common for me.

00:07:59.820 --> 00:08:04.339
I start with these two lines of code at the top of my scripts.

00:08:04.339 --> 00:08:07.380
So I have the Tidyverse and data table.

00:08:07.380 --> 00:08:12.700
Note that the approaches that I show you today actually work with the developmental

00:08:12.700 --> 00:08:14.260
version of data table.

00:08:14.260 --> 00:08:16.339
But there are other ways of doing this.

00:08:16.339 --> 00:08:20.260
This is just the way that it's going to work going forward.

00:08:20.260 --> 00:08:24.440
So I want to present that.

00:08:24.440 --> 00:08:29.940
So the two data sets we're going to play around with, the dplyr ones at top one, it has the

00:08:29.940 --> 00:08:31.700
name of the character.

00:08:31.700 --> 00:08:37.059
It has their species, their home world, and then it has, oh, no, there's a list column.

00:08:37.059 --> 00:08:38.059
It shows up already.

00:08:38.059 --> 00:08:40.140
So we have films.

00:08:40.140 --> 00:08:46.340
So it's a character vector of the films that, for example, on the first row that Luke Skywalker

00:08:46.340 --> 00:08:47.340
is in.

00:08:47.340 --> 00:08:51.119
It has five films listed.

00:08:51.119 --> 00:08:54.419
The other data set, it's a revenue data set, and it's by film.

00:08:54.419 --> 00:09:00.820
So A New Hope made $775 million, roughly.

00:09:00.820 --> 00:09:04.419
And you can look through the rest when we get to that.

00:09:04.419 --> 00:09:13.700
So these two, if our goal is to understand how things in the first data set relate to

00:09:13.700 --> 00:09:17.659
revenue for the movies, we're going to have to do some work to get it in that format.

00:09:17.659 --> 00:09:22.219
Because right now, we couldn't join these very easily.

00:09:22.219 --> 00:09:29.820
So just to get us to where so we have a framework we're working from, you are here at the tidying

00:09:29.979 --> 00:09:34.380
and transforming steps of the data work life.

00:09:34.380 --> 00:09:37.179
Again, this is from Allison.

00:09:37.179 --> 00:09:38.460
Beautiful.

00:09:38.460 --> 00:09:41.380
Just makes me happy looking at it.

00:09:41.380 --> 00:09:47.059
So one of our issues right here that we have to deal with is that one of the data sets

00:09:47.059 --> 00:09:48.140
is at the film level.

00:09:48.140 --> 00:09:50.619
So we have per film the revenue.

00:09:50.619 --> 00:09:53.179
And the other one is at the character level.

00:09:53.179 --> 00:09:56.539
By character, we have information about them.

00:09:56.539 --> 00:10:01.419
And so they're not in a format that we can easily join them so that we can look at things

00:10:01.419 --> 00:10:02.940
together.

00:10:02.940 --> 00:10:06.500
So the first thing we're going to do is unnest.

00:10:06.500 --> 00:10:09.979
So we're going to unnest the films column.

00:10:09.979 --> 00:10:14.000
It's, again, a list column of character vectors.

00:10:14.000 --> 00:10:17.539
And so the first thing we're going to do is we're going to let R know that we're going

00:10:17.539 --> 00:10:19.219
to be using data table.

00:10:19.219 --> 00:10:22.580
This is one of the really important steps to use in data table.

00:10:22.580 --> 00:10:27.260
In order for the square brackets to work, you have to tell R that it's a data table.

00:10:27.260 --> 00:10:31.340
So in this one, we're just grabbing it straight from the dplyr package.

00:10:31.340 --> 00:10:33.580
And we're just letting it know that it's a data table.

00:10:33.580 --> 00:10:38.260
We'll call it sw here.

00:10:38.260 --> 00:10:40.580
And then this is where the unnesting happens.

00:10:40.580 --> 00:10:45.520
So if you remember what we were talking about before, you can look at the placeholder.

00:10:45.520 --> 00:10:48.659
So you have a placeholder here for i.

00:10:48.659 --> 00:10:52.080
In this case, we're not going to be filtering or arranging.

00:10:52.080 --> 00:10:56.559
So we just leave that blank, do a comma.

00:10:56.559 --> 00:11:02.039
And then this placeholder is for like things that you would do in mutate.

00:11:02.039 --> 00:11:08.320
Here we're creating a new column or, in essence, replacing it.

00:11:08.320 --> 00:11:20.039
By taking the elements we're unlisting here in the currently list column called films.

00:11:20.039 --> 00:11:26.640
And then in the by statement, we're just going to put all the other variables that

00:11:26.640 --> 00:11:34.080
are at the character level that we want to hold on to, for example, like name and species.

00:11:34.080 --> 00:11:35.840
So this produces this data set.

00:11:35.840 --> 00:11:44.320
So now instead of just one Luke Skywalker row and the films being shoved into a single

00:11:44.320 --> 00:11:52.080
cell, now we have the name and we have each film as a row.

00:11:52.080 --> 00:12:00.320
So we can see that Luke was in Revenge of the Sith, Return of the Jedi, et cetera.

00:12:00.320 --> 00:12:04.039
Next I propose that we actually do another nesting.

00:12:04.039 --> 00:12:07.419
So we're not getting away from the list columns that easy.

00:12:07.419 --> 00:12:13.559
So we're going to create here a new column called data.

00:12:13.559 --> 00:12:16.679
And what we're going to do is we're going to create a list column.

00:12:16.679 --> 00:12:18.960
That's what this is doing.

00:12:18.960 --> 00:12:20.919
Of this symbol.

00:12:20.919 --> 00:12:22.039
It's .sd.

00:12:22.039 --> 00:12:28.000
And if you haven't used data table very much before, you can think of it as the subset

00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:29.000
of the data.

00:12:29.000 --> 00:12:31.359
So sd for subset of data.

00:12:31.359 --> 00:12:39.000
And in this case, that subset is going to be everything that's not in the by statement.

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:41.119
So what does this produce?

00:12:41.119 --> 00:12:42.500
This.

00:12:42.500 --> 00:12:49.500
So now by film, we have the associated data in a single cell.

00:12:49.500 --> 00:12:51.659
So we have a new hope.

00:12:51.659 --> 00:12:56.020
And all the data that goes with the new hope is now comfortably packed into that single

00:12:56.020 --> 00:13:01.780
cell as a data table.

00:13:01.780 --> 00:13:03.859
So now we actually can join them.

00:13:03.859 --> 00:13:08.500
And I suggest that this is a great way of doing this.

00:13:08.500 --> 00:13:14.659
In data table, one way to join is you have one data table.

00:13:14.659 --> 00:13:19.380
And then the first part of the square bracket in the I part, you actually put another data

00:13:19.380 --> 00:13:20.380
table.

00:13:20.380 --> 00:13:22.000
So revenue is another data table.

00:13:22.000 --> 00:13:24.780
And then you tell it what you're joining on.

00:13:24.780 --> 00:13:28.380
And this is a really fast form of joining.

00:13:28.380 --> 00:13:30.859
When you print this out, this is what we now have.

00:13:30.859 --> 00:13:35.099
So we have per film, we have the associated data.

00:13:35.099 --> 00:13:37.580
And we have revenue.

00:13:37.659 --> 00:13:44.940
So the reason why I think nesting before we joined was really useful is, I don't know,

00:13:44.940 --> 00:13:46.539
you don't have to raise hands to admit it.

00:13:46.539 --> 00:13:52.340
But has anyone made a mistake joining data or been surprised by the result when you're

00:13:52.340 --> 00:13:53.619
joining data?

00:13:53.619 --> 00:13:57.299
If so, you're human.

00:13:57.299 --> 00:13:59.260
I've done it numerous times.

00:13:59.260 --> 00:14:02.940
And it's usually like a misspelling in one of the keys.

00:14:02.940 --> 00:14:06.500
There's a million ways that things can go wrong when you're joining data.

00:14:06.500 --> 00:14:11.859
And so one way to make it simpler is actually using this nesting.

00:14:11.859 --> 00:14:18.140
And so all we had to look for was the key and anything that the new data set's bringing

00:14:18.140 --> 00:14:19.140
in.

00:14:19.140 --> 00:14:20.940
And now it's really easy to problem solve.

00:14:20.940 --> 00:14:24.979
I can look through if there's a surprise or one of the revenues wasn't there.

00:14:24.979 --> 00:14:27.099
I would be able to find out really quickly.

00:14:27.099 --> 00:14:35.940
Whereas, if my data set was really long and not nested, it would be much harder.

00:14:35.940 --> 00:14:40.059
So now that we have the data sets together, we actually can do some analyses.

00:14:40.059 --> 00:14:47.739
Here, like I mentioned before, all of this happening here is mutate.

00:14:47.739 --> 00:14:51.500
But this time, we have this what is called the walrus operator.

00:14:51.500 --> 00:14:53.419
That's my favorite name for an operator.

00:14:53.419 --> 00:14:57.059
And you can see why it's called a walrus operator, right?

00:14:57.059 --> 00:14:58.099
The teeth.

00:14:58.099 --> 00:15:04.219
So what it's doing is it's creating a new variable called counts.

00:15:04.219 --> 00:15:07.900
And it's reaching into each cell of data.

00:15:07.900 --> 00:15:11.979
That's a column that we have in our data table.

00:15:11.979 --> 00:15:19.739
And we're using count to just get the count by each species in the data that we have.

00:15:19.739 --> 00:15:25.539
What this operator does that's different than what we're normally used to in R is that it's

00:15:25.539 --> 00:15:28.380
going to modify in place.

00:15:28.380 --> 00:15:32.539
And this is a nuance that is important when you start using data table.

00:15:32.539 --> 00:15:37.580
Because it is changing SWN, that object, in place.

00:15:37.580 --> 00:15:38.619
It's not making a copy.

00:15:38.619 --> 00:15:41.619
It's just changing it right there.

00:15:41.619 --> 00:15:47.020
And so you don't actually have any assignment towards the end of this.

00:15:47.020 --> 00:15:52.940
This actually takes care of the assignment, which is sometimes a hurdle for people to

00:15:52.940 --> 00:15:56.900
get used to as they're getting in there.

00:15:56.900 --> 00:15:59.900
So this is going to create a list column again.

00:15:59.900 --> 00:16:05.099
But this time using per map of counts by each.

00:16:05.099 --> 00:16:07.859
And I have an outdated thing there.

00:16:07.859 --> 00:16:11.419
It's by species instead of gender.

00:16:11.419 --> 00:16:16.059
You'll notice at the end of the object, I keep putting the square brackets.

00:16:16.059 --> 00:16:20.460
That forces the print in data table.

00:16:20.460 --> 00:16:23.580
When you use this operator, sometimes it doesn't print.

00:16:23.580 --> 00:16:27.340
And so when you are using data table, this is a great way to force it to print if you

00:16:27.340 --> 00:16:29.700
want it to.

00:16:29.700 --> 00:16:31.419
And now, last step.

00:16:31.419 --> 00:16:33.619
We're just about there.

00:16:33.619 --> 00:16:41.539
Now we're going to unnest a list column that has data tables in it or tables in this case

00:16:41.539 --> 00:16:42.539
instead of vectors.

00:16:42.539 --> 00:16:46.059
So this time we don't actually need to give it a name like we did before.

00:16:46.059 --> 00:16:47.760
Now we're just unnesting it.

00:16:47.760 --> 00:16:49.880
So this is the new variable.

00:16:49.880 --> 00:16:56.039
And we're just grabbing that and unnesting by film and revenue.

00:16:56.039 --> 00:16:59.520
And what this is going to do is it's just going to grab everything in each of those

00:16:59.520 --> 00:17:09.239
individual data sets and it's just going to unnest it so it looks like a normal data table.

00:17:09.239 --> 00:17:10.239
So this is what we get.

00:17:10.239 --> 00:17:15.719
We get for a new hope, we can see the revenue that's tied to it.

00:17:15.760 --> 00:17:20.160
We can see that there are three droids in a new hope.

00:17:20.160 --> 00:17:26.400
If you're familiar with the movies, you probably can list off what droids those are.

00:17:26.400 --> 00:17:29.680
For a new hope, there's 12 humans, et cetera.

00:17:29.680 --> 00:17:34.199
And from here, we can get proportions and things and we could possibly come up with

00:17:34.199 --> 00:17:41.319
this and see how revenue is associated with how many, the percent of the major characters

00:17:41.319 --> 00:17:43.439
being human in a movie.

00:17:43.439 --> 00:17:46.439
The Force Awakens really throws things off because that's the new one.

00:17:46.439 --> 00:17:48.719
It made a ton of money.

00:17:48.719 --> 00:17:53.520
But for the most part, it looked like people watched it less if there were more humans.

00:17:53.520 --> 00:17:58.719
We just like, we want other stuff.

00:17:58.719 --> 00:18:02.359
But at this point, you're like, okay, cool, whatever.

00:18:02.359 --> 00:18:05.479
We're here for the performance.

00:18:05.479 --> 00:18:10.439
And it is actually kind of cool looking at performance when you're working with packages

00:18:10.439 --> 00:18:11.439
like this.

00:18:11.439 --> 00:18:17.959
So we've packaged up some of these functions to make them easier to test and to use.

00:18:17.959 --> 00:18:18.959
It's in TidyFast.

00:18:18.959 --> 00:18:22.119
If you're interested, it's on GitHub.

00:18:22.119 --> 00:18:25.920
And so for nesting, this is a really small dataset.

00:18:25.920 --> 00:18:30.079
But you already start to see some improvement.

00:18:30.079 --> 00:18:34.079
The place that you see a lot of improvement with nesting is the memory that it uses to

00:18:34.079 --> 00:18:37.359
do the operation.

00:18:37.359 --> 00:18:45.719
So the improvement in performance, both with memory and time, actually grows as your dataset

00:18:45.719 --> 00:18:51.719
gets bigger and bigger and as you have more and more groups.

00:18:51.719 --> 00:18:57.160
So as your data gets more complicated and bigger, the benefits grow.

00:18:57.160 --> 00:18:59.439
For unnesting, similar thing.

00:18:59.439 --> 00:19:04.359
You do see benefit even with a small dataset.

00:19:04.359 --> 00:19:06.160
But again, it grows.

00:19:06.160 --> 00:19:12.920
The benefits grow with the size of the data and the complexity of it.

00:19:12.920 --> 00:19:15.599
So that's everything I have for you.

00:19:15.599 --> 00:19:21.520
I hope you got to see a little bit how DataTable can be integrated into your work, that it's

00:19:21.520 --> 00:19:29.180
definitely not a replacement of anything in dplyr or vice versa, that they're very complementary.

00:19:29.180 --> 00:19:30.560
This is the picture slide.

00:19:30.560 --> 00:19:34.839
If you want to find all the resources that are tied to me, take a picture.

00:19:34.839 --> 00:19:41.439
I'm really grateful for the DataTable team, everything they've done, and for Julie and

00:19:41.439 --> 00:19:44.199
Allison for letting me use their beautiful art.

00:19:44.199 --> 00:19:45.199
Thank you.

00:19:45.199 --> 00:19:46.199
Thank you, Tyson.

00:19:46.199 --> 00:19:55.079
I think we have time for one or two questions.

00:19:55.079 --> 00:20:03.680
First one from William Chu asks, what did you use as DataTable rather than SetDT?

00:20:03.680 --> 00:20:09.079
So the SetDT will replace the object in place.

00:20:09.079 --> 00:20:16.599
And so when the dataset's not huge, I recommend using as.DataTable, because it creates a copy,

00:20:16.599 --> 00:20:22.920
and then you're not going to be modifying your first object, whatever that was before.

00:20:22.920 --> 00:20:28.239
When your data get really big and you don't want to make copies, then SetDT is the way

00:20:28.239 --> 00:20:29.239
forward.

00:20:29.239 --> 00:20:30.239
Thank you.

00:20:30.239 --> 00:20:31.239
Great question.

00:20:31.239 --> 00:20:36.920
The second question is, what are your next steps for TidyFast?

00:20:36.920 --> 00:20:41.239
So it's a great question.

00:20:41.239 --> 00:20:47.520
As of right now, TidyFast is more trying to implement tidy R functions with DataTable

00:20:47.520 --> 00:20:54.000
as the back end, because I didn't want to even try to compete with something like DTplyr.

00:20:54.000 --> 00:20:55.839
It's a fantastic package.

00:20:55.839 --> 00:20:58.719
So it's mostly tidy R functions.

00:20:58.719 --> 00:21:04.920
It's testing, bug fixing, and just improving the package.

